\end_inset

 which means that a debt is treated differently, depending on how long is
 it overdue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ratios
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Current ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This ratio designed to explore the ability to collect receivables.
 Current ratio is assets divided by liabilities.
 The higher the number is - the less risky the company is.
 In this ratio there is a trade-off between risk and efficiency.
 A higher number means less risk, but also less efficiency.
 A decent current ratio today is 1 ot a bit more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an example: having 0.8 at the end of the year, and one of the loan
 has a covenant which requires it to be 0.82 or above.
 By lowering the ADA it is possible to tweak that ratio, which can also
 be done by taking another loan.
 Companies constantly do is, as it is the responsibility of the finance
 department to ensure that the company does not violate debt covenance,
 and it is completely legal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quick Ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quick ratio is the sum of cash, marketable securities and the A/R, divided
 by the current liabilities and is somewhat similar to the current ratio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A/R Turnover
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sales divided by the average A/R provide the A/R turnover.
 It measures how effective a firm is in collecting debts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Days of receivables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How many days it takes for the firm to collect its cash.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an example with a firm whose ratio increases from 29-30 days to
 32.
 It might be an indication of having difficulties collecting debts.
 If a company is forces to give more credit, it means that it is harder
 for it to sell, which can be a sign of slowing down economical activity.
 The only way to avoid being asked that question is to (legally) manipulate
 the numbers, and bring it back down to 30.
 It can be done by using a financial institution, which buys the A/R and
 gives cash.
\end_layout

